 into the twentieth century. In particular, Berry argues that an explicitly Christian understanding of salvation underlies the movement’s orientation toward the natural world. Theologically derived concepts of salvation, redemption, and spiritual progress have not only provided the basic context for Americans’ passion for nature but have also established the horizons of possibility within the national environmental imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnvironmentalismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aEnvironmentalismzUnited States. 0aHuman ecologyxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aHuman ecologyzUnited States. 0aNaturexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / General.2bisacsh  a20th century environmentalist.  aamerican environmentalism.  aamerican religious history.  achristianity.  aenvironmental historians.  aenvironmental history.  aenvironmental science.  aenvironmentalism.  agilded age environmentalism.  agilded age religion.  ahistory.  ahuman ecology.  anature and science.  aprogressive era environmentalism.  aprogressive era religion.  areligion and nature.  areligious elements in environmentalism.  areligious environmentalism.  areligious studies.  asacred space.  ascientists.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028573640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096114240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961142423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961142/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY